Title:
Catching Credential Guard Off Guard

Type:
Blog Post

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
This post presents new credential extraction techniques that remain viable on fully patched Windows 11 and Windows Server 2025 systems with modern protections like Credential Guard (VBS/IUM) enabled. It focuses on bypassing the traditional “dump LSASS” approach by interacting with Credential Guard indirectly via Remote Credential Guard (RCG) and the Terminal Services/CredSSP authentication stack. The author reverse engineers and reimplements parts of the Terminal Services SSP (TsPkg.dll), and later the Negotiate SSP and Kerberos SSP, to gain the necessary security context for encrypting/decrypting CredSSP/RCG payloads and invoking KerbCredIsoRemote/NtlmCredIsoRemote interfaces. A key outcome is the ability to obtain chosen-challenge NTLMv1 responses (notably for the static challenge 1122334455667788) even when Microsoft documentation suggests Credential Guard should prevent this, enabling fast NT-hash recovery via rainbow tables and subsequent PtH/Kerberos key abuse. The technique can work unprivileged for the current user given an SPN-bearing account (e.g., a machine account created via Powermad), and can be extended with SYSTEM to target other logged-on sessions via token impersonation or via MSV1_0 package calls on RDP servers hosting RCG sessions. It includes defensive notes (limited visibility; suggests monitoring LsaCallAuthenticationPackage and NTLMv1 challenge patterns) and links to a PoC tool (“DumpGuard”).

Technical Focus:
- Windows Credential Guard internals (VBS, Secure Kernel, IUM/lsaiso.exe, CredIso interfaces)
- SSPI/LSA interaction (AcquireCredentialsHandle, InitializeSecurityContext, AcceptSecurityContext, LsaCallAuthenticationPackage)
- Remote Credential Guard (MS-RDPEAR) and CredSSP (MS-CSSP) protocol mechanics
- Reverse engineering/reimplementation of TsPkg (Terminal Services SSP), Negotiate SSP, Kerberos SSP
- NTLMv1 chosen-challenge response generation and NT-hash recovery (rainbow tables)
- Kerberos ticket handling under Credential Guard (TGT protection vs usable TGS)

Use Cases:
- Extract crackable credential material on Credential Guard–protected endpoints without LSASS dumping
- Generate NTLMv1 responses for targeted cracking/NT-hash recovery (e.g., static challenge lookups)
- Post-exploitation lateral movement via recovered NT hash (PtH) and Kerberos RC4 key usage
- Red team tradecraft for operating in environments with PPL + EDR LSASS protections
- Defensive research: build detections around LSA package calls and anomalous NTLMv1 challenge usage

Keywords:
Credential Guard, VBS, Secure Kernel, Isolated User Mode, lsaiso.exe, lsass.exe, SSPI, LSA, LsaCallAuthenticationPackage, TsPkg.dll, CredSSP, MS-CSSP, Remote Credential Guard, MS-RDPEAR, KerbCredIsoRemote, NtlmCredIsoRemote, Kerberos, NTLMv1, MSV1_0, AcquireCredentialsHandle, InitializeSecurityContext, AcceptSecurityContext, EncryptMessage, DecryptMessage, ALPC, RPC type serialization, SPN, machine account, Powermad, Pass-the-Hash